\begin{align*} \frac{a^2+b^2}{2} - \left(\frac{a+b}{2}\right)^2 &= \frac{2(a^2+b^2) - (a+b)^2}{4} \\ &= \frac{2a^2+2b^2 - (a^2+2ab+b^2)}{4} \\ &= \frac{a^2-2ab+b^2}{4} \\ &= \frac{(a-b)^2}{4} \ge 0 \end{align*}
Since $a$ and $b$ are real numbers, $(a-b)^2 \ge 0$, thus $\frac{(a-b)^2}{4} \ge 0$.
Therefore, $\frac{a^2+b^2}{2} - \left(\frac{a+b}{2}\right)^2 \ge 0$, which implies $\left(\frac{a+b}{2}\right)^2 \leq \frac{a^2+b^2}{2}$.
